Explanations regarding global competitiveness
In November, the World Economic Forum and the Harvard University Center for International Development published the Global Competitiveness Report (Competitiveness Report) for the year 2001.
In the study encompassing 75 countries, Finland, the United States, and Canada occupy the top three positions, while Nicaragua, Nigeria, and Zimbabwe lag behind.
(All rankings can be found at www.weforum.com.)
As co-leader of this annual study, I am often asked what competitiveness actually means.
Is there also an economic competition among the countries besides the military one?
Is it even meaningful to say that Finland is more competitive than, for example, Germany or Italy?
In our report, competitiveness is defined with great precision: namely as a country's ability to achieve sustainable economic growth over a medium-term period—specifically, a timeframe of five years.
This definition, however, does not mean that the competitiveness of one country simultaneously says something about the lack of competitiveness of another country.
With better political strategies, all countries on Earth could simultaneously achieve higher growth.
It is still meaningful to create a ranking of countries in terms of their growth potential.
Each country is interested in knowing whether its political strategies and public institutions can keep pace with those of other countries in terms of their ability to achieve sustainable economic growth.
In some ways, economic growth can be compared to a sporting competition, where the gains of one country or region come at the expense of another country or region.
Countries compete, for example, for internationally mobile capital.
The more investment a country attracts from foreign direct investments, the less another country receives.
This becomes clear when countries vie for a specific investment project.
When Intel plans a new semiconductor plant, various countries are invited to submit offers.
The bidding for the contract is intense, and often involves tax incentives, infrastructure improvements, and even adjustments to local technical university study programs.
This year, we assessed a country's competitiveness (growth potential) based on three broad criteria: (1) technology, (2) public institutions, and (3) macroeconomic stability.
For each of these categories, we calculated indicators whose average values were computed using a specific method to then create a general growth and competitiveness index.
The criterion technology refers to a country's ability to drive new developments and adopt technologies developed elsewhere.
Some countries like the United States, Japan, South Korea, Israel, and Sweden invest heavily in research and development and thus achieve high values in terms of innovation.
Other countries like Argentina and Brazil invest less in research and development and thus achieve little in terms of new products and processes.
Innovation-friendly countries also enjoy a high prosperity due to these innovations.
In this area, the United States, Canada, and Finland occupy the top three spots on the ranking list.
The criterion "public institutions" refers to the quality of administration.
Is corruption a widespread problem?
Are the courts impartial and free from corruption?
Can one rely on the government fulfilling its obligations according to regulations?
Countries with functioning public institutions achieve higher growth rates than countries with corrupt officials and biased judges.
High ethical standards enhance economic performance.
In this regard, the Nordic countries are world leaders, and Finland, Iceland, and Denmark also top the ranking list.
Corruption is virtually unknown in these countries.
Macroeconomic stability is defined by the absence of inflation, a balanced government budget, a realistic exchange rate of the national currency, the ability of companies and the government to obtain loans on the capital market, and high confidence that the government will fulfill its financial obligations.
As an example from Asia in the late 1990s, we have learned that a macroeconomic crisis can undermine economic growth, even if the companies are internationally competitive.
The three leading countries regarding macroeconomic stability are Singapore, Ireland, and Switzerland.
In our studies on competitiveness, we have noticed that the world economy can be divided into two categories of countries: those that are innovative and those that are not innovative.
Only about 20 countries actively engage in developing new technologies.
In these countries, which are among the wealthiest in the world, a superior system of technological innovation is regarded as a prerequisite for sustained competitiveness.
The universities must be excellent, state laboratories should have world-class standards, and government and industry should heavily invest in research and development.
A key factor for future growth in these economies is the proportion of students who attend secondary schools and universities after completing compulsory education.
In the United States and Canada, this proportion amounts to 80%.
For the "non-innovative" countries, technology is just as important, but most new technologies are imported from abroad and not developed within the country itself.
Some countries specialize in importing new technologies, while others do so to a lesser extent.
In the past ten or fifteen years, most technology imports have occurred as part of foreign direct investments.
American firms that invested heavily in Mexico or Taiwanese firms that invested on the Chinese mainland also brought in new technologies that increased the efficiency of production in the respective target economies.
Therefore, it was certainly worthwhile for the affected countries to strive vigorously for these foreign investments: they bring not only capital but also new technologies.
One strength and at the same time a weakness of our analysis of competitiveness is that it is oriented towards the medium term and does not focus on the next one to two years.
Our rankings are not suitable for assessing short-term cyclical changes in an economy, but they do provide insight into the long-term prospects of major economies.
It is therefore ironic that many of the countries that placed first this year, such as the United States or Singapore, are actually in a recession, while other lower-ranked countries, such as China (ranked 39th), are not affected by the global recession.
Partly, the slowdown of the economy is linked to the September 11 attacks, but it is increasingly clear that the American economy and other economies connected to it through trade and production networks were already sliding into recession before September.
We believe, however, that this is a temporary cyclical downturn, and that the United States will regain its ability to achieve strong economic growth over the next five years.
